com.github.dylon.liblevenshtein.levenshtein

Interface ISubsumesFunction

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Serializable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    SubsumesFunction, SubsumesFunction.ForMergeAndSplit, SubsumesFunction.ForStandardAlgorithm, SubsumesFunction.ForTransposition

    public interface ISubsumesFunction
extends Serializable
    Determines whether the position represented by the combination of parameters in the left half subsumes the position represented by the combination of parameters in the right half.
    Since:
    2.1.0

    • Method Summary

      All Methods Instance Methods Abstract Methods 
      Modifier and Type Method and Description
      boolean at(int i, int e, int j, int f)
      Determines whether the standard, Levenshtein state represented by (i,e) subsumes the other, represented by (j,f).
      boolean at(int i, int e, int s, int j, int f, int t, int n)
      Determines whether the transposition or merge-and-split, Levenshtein state represented by (i,e,s) subsumes the other, represented by (j,f,t), under the maximum number of errors, n.

    • Method Detail

      • at

        boolean at(int i,
           int e,
           int j,
           int f)
        Determines whether the standard, Levenshtein state represented by (i,e) subsumes the other, represented by (j,f).
        Parameters:
        i - Index of the spelling candidate of the first position.
        e - Number of accumulated errors of the spelling candidate at index i of the first position.
        j - Index of the spelling candidate of the second position.
        f - Number of accumulated errors of the spelling candidate at index j of the second position.
        Returns:
        Whether (i,e) subsumes (j,f)

      • at

        boolean at(int i,
           int e,
           int s,
           int j,
           int f,
           int t,
           int n)
        Determines whether the transposition or merge-and-split, Levenshtein state represented by (i,e,s) subsumes the other, represented by (j,f,t), under the maximum number of errors, n.
        Parameters:
        i - Index of the spelling candidate of the first position.
        e - Number of accumulated errors of the spelling candidate at index i of the first position.
        s - Either 0 or 1, depending on whether the first position is a regular state or a special case (e.g. transposition, merge, or split).
        j - Index of the spelling candidate of the second position.
        f - Number of accumulated errors of the spelling candidate at index j of the second position.
        t - Either 0 or 1, depending on whether the second position is a regular state or a special case (e.g. transposition, merge, or split).
        n - Maximum number of errors allowed in spelling candidates.
        Returns:
        Whether (i,e,s) subsumes (j,f,t)
